The medical home,[1] also known as the patient-centered medical home (PCMH), is a team based health care delivery model led by a physician, P.A., or N.P. that provides comprehensive and continuous medical care to patients with the goal of obtaining maximized health outcomes (American College of Physicians) (American Academy of Family Physicians). It is "an approach to providing comprehensive primary care for children, youth and adults".[2] The provision of medical homes may allow better access to health care, increase satisfaction with care, and improve health.[3][4][5][6] 
Joint principles that define a PCMH have been established through the cohesive efforts of the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP), American Academy of Family Physicians (AAFP), American College of Physicians (ACP), and American Osteopathic Association (AOA). (Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative)
Care coordination is an essential component of the PCMH. Care coordination requires additional resources such as health information technology, and appropriately trained staff to provide coordinated care through team-based models. Additionally, payment models that compensate PCMHs for their effort devoted to care coordination activities and patient-centered care management that fall outside the face-face patient encounter may help encourage coordination (Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative) (National Academy of Sciences, 1996). 


==History==
The concept of the "medical home" has evolved since introduction of the terminology by the [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] in 1967, which was envisioned at the time as a central source for all the medical information about a child, especially those with special needs.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://books.google.com/?id=GZuVbzss5WoC&pg=PA42&dq=Palfrey+medical+home+1970s#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = Child health in America: Making a difference through advocacy | isbn = 978-0-8018-8453-5 | author1 = Palfrey | first1 = Judith | date = 2006-10-31}}</ref><ref>http://facm.unjbg.edu.pe/revistaspediatria/Clinical%20Pediatrics/2009/August/16%20The%20Medical%20Home-Improving%20Quality%20of%20Primary%20Care%20for%20Children.pdf</ref> Efforts by Dr. [[Calvin C.J. Sia]], a Honolulu-based pediatrician, to pursue new approaches to improve early childhood development in Hawaii in the 1980s<ref name=Sia2004>{{cite journal |author=Sia C, Tonniges TF, Osterhus E, Taba S |title=History of the medical home concept |journal=Pediatrics |volume=113 |issue=5 Suppl |pages=1473–8 |year=2004 |month=May |pmid=15121914 |url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=15121914}}</ref> laid the groundwork for an Academy policy statement in 1992 that defined a medical home largely the way Sia conceived it: a strategy for delivering the family-centered, comprehensive, continuous and coordinated care that all infants and children deserve.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://books.google.com/?id=GZuVbzss5WoC&pg=PA42&dq=Palfrey+Cal+Sia+medical+home#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = Child health in America: Making a difference through advocacy | isbn = 978-0-8018-8453-5 | author1 = Palfrey | first1 = Judith | date = 2006-10-31}}</ref> In 2002, the organization expanded and operationalized the definition.<ref name=Sia2004/><ref>{{cite journal|author= Ad Hoc Task Force on Definition of the Medical Home|title=American Academy of Pediatrics Ad Hoc Task Force on Definition of the Medical Home: The medical home |journal=Pediatrics |volume=90 |issue=5 |pages=774 |year=1992 |month=November |pmid=1408554 |url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=1408554}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author= |title=The medical home |journal=Pediatrics |volume=110 |issue=1 Pt 1 |pages=184–6 |year=2002 |month=July |pmid=12093969 |doi=10.1542/peds.110.1.184 |author1=Medical Home Initiatives for Children With Special Needs Project Advisory Committee. American Academy of Pediatrics}}</ref>

In 2002, seven U.S. national [[family medicine]] organizations created the ''Future of Family Medicine'' project to "transform and renew the specialty of family medicine."<ref name=FFM>{{cite journal |author=Martin JC |title=The Future of Family Medicine: A Collaborative Project of the Family Medicine Community |journal=[[Annals of Family Medicine]] |volume=2 Suppl 1 |issue= Suppl 1|pages=S3–32 |year=2004 |pmid=15080220 |pmc=1466763 |doi=10.1370/afm.130 |author-separator=, |author2=Avant RF |author3=Bowman MA |display-authors=3 |last4=Bucholtz |first4=JR |last5=Dickinson |first5=JR |last6=Evans |first6=KL |last7=Green |first7=LA |last8=Henley |first8=DE |last9=Jones |first9=WA}}</ref>  Among the recommendations of the project was that every American should have a "personal medical home" through which to receive his or her [[Acute (medicine)|acute]], [[Chronic (medical)|chronic]], and [[Preventive medicine|preventive]] services.<ref name=FFM/> The services should be "accessible, accountable, comprehensive, integrated, patient-centered, safe, scientifically valid, and satisfying to both patients and their physicians."<ref name=FFM/>

As of 2004, one study estimated that if the ''Future of Family Medicine'' recommendations were followed (including implementation of personal medical homes), "health care costs would likely decrease by 5.6%, resulting in national savings of 67 billion dollars per year, with an improvement in the quality of the health care provided."<ref>{{cite journal |author=Spann SJ |title=Task Force Report 6. Report on Financing the New Model of Family Medicine |journal=Annals of Family Medicine |volume=2 Suppl 3 |issue= Suppl 3|pages=S1–21 |year=2004 |month=December |pmid=15654084 |pmc=1466777 |doi=10.1370/afm.237 |author2=Task Force 6 and the Executive Editorial Team}}</ref> A review of the literature published the same year determined that medical homes are "associated with better health, ... with lower overall costs of care and with reductions in disparities in health."<ref>{{cite journal |author=Starfield B, Shi L |title=The medical home, access to care, and insurance: a review of evidence |journal=Pediatrics |volume=113 |issue=5 Suppl |pages=1493–8 |year=2004 |month=May |pmid=15121917|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=15121917  }}</ref> 

By 2005, the [[American College of Physicians]] had developed an "advanced medical home" model.<ref name=Rosenthal2008>{{cite journal |author=Sutton MA, Gibbons RP, Correa RJ |title=Is deleting the digital rectal examination a good idea? |journal=[[The Western Journal of Medicine]] |volume=155 |issue=1 |pages=43–6 |year=1991 |month=July |pmid=1877229 |pmc=1002909 |doi=10.3122/jabfm.2008.05.070287}}</ref><ref name=ACP2005>{{cite journal |author=Barr M, Ginsburg J |url=http://www.acponline.org/advocacy/where_we_stand/policy/adv_med.pdf |title=The advanced medical home: a patient-centered, physician-guided model of health care. A policy monograph of the American College of Physicians |publisher=American College of Physicians |year=2005 |accessdate=2009 Jul 8}}</ref> The model involved the use of [[evidence-based medicine]], clinical decision support tools, the Chronic Care Model, medical care plans, "enhanced and convenient" access to care, quantitative indicators of quality, health information technology, and feedback on performance.<ref name=ACP2005/> Payment reform was recognized as important to implement the model.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Goroll AH, Berenson RA, Schoenbaum SC, Gardner LB |title=Fundamental Reform of Payment for Adult Primary Care: Comprehensive Payment for Comprehensive Care |journal=[[Journal of General Internal Medicine]] |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=410–5 |year=2007 |month=March |pmid=17356977 |pmc=1824766 |doi=10.1007/s11606-006-0083-2}}</ref>

[[IBM]] and other organizations started the [[Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative]] in 2006 to promote the medical home model.<ref name=Backer2009>{{cite journal |author=Backer LA |title=Building the case for the patient-centered medical home |journal=[[Family Practice Management]] |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=14–8 |year=2009 |pmid=19186734 |url=http://www.aafp.org/link_out?pmid=19186734}}</ref><ref name=Arnst2009>{{cite news |author=Arnst C |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/09_27/b4138034173005.htm |title=The family doctor: a remedy for health-care costs? |work=[[BusinessWeek]] |date=2009-06-25 |accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref> As of 2009, its membership included "some 500 large employers, insurers, consumer groups, and doctors."<ref name=Arnst2009/>

In 2007, the [[American Academy of Family Physicians]], [[American Academy of Pediatrics]], [[American College of Physicians]], and [[American Osteopathic Association]] — the largest primary care physician organizations in the United States — released the ''Joint Principles of the Patient-Centered Medical Home.''<ref name=JointPrinciples>{{cite web |author=[[American Academy of Family Physicians]], [[American Academy of Pediatrics]], [[American College of Physicians]], and [[American Osteopathic Association]]. |url=http://www.acponline.org/hpp/approve_jp.pdf |title=Joint principles of the patient-centered medical home |date=2007 Mar |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>  The principles listed were: 
*'''Personal physician''': "each patient has an ongoing relationship with a personal physician trained to provide first contact, continuous and comprehensive care."
*'''Physician directed medical practice''':  "the personal physician leads a team of individuals at the practice level who collectively take responsibility for the ongoing care of patients."
*'''Whole person orientation''': "the personal physician is responsible for providing for all the patient’s health care needs or taking responsibility for appropriately arranging care with other qualified professionals."
•	Care is coordinated and/or integrated: Care is coordinated and/or integrated between complex health care systems, for example across specialists, hospitals, home health agencies, and nursing homes, and also includes the patient’s loved ones and community-based services. This goal can be attained though the utilization of registries, health information technology and exchanges, ensuring patients receive culturally and linguistically appropriate care (Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative).

•	Quality and safety 
-	Partnerships between the patient, physicians and their family are an integral part of the medical home. Practices are encouraged to advocate for their patients and provide compassionate quality, patient-centered care
-	Guide decision making based on evidence based medicine and with the use of decision-support tools
-	Physician’s voluntary engagement in performance measurements to continuously gauge quality improvement
-	Patients are involved in decision making and provide feedback to determine if their expectations are met
-	Utilization of informational technology to ensure optimum patient care, performance measurement, patient education, and enhanced communication
-	At the practice level, patients and their families participate in quality improvement activities
-	 (Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative). 

•	Enhanced access to care is available through open scheduling and extended hours and new options for  (Balara & Harper) (Patient-Centered Primary Care Collaborative).

•	Payment must "appropriately recognize the added value provided to patients who have a patient-centered medical home." 
-	Payment should reflect the time physician and non-physician staff spend doing patient-centered care management work outside the face-to-face visit
-	Services involved with coordination of care should be paid for
-	It should support measurement of quality and efficiency with the use and adoption of health information technology (Batesm & Bitton, 2010)
-	Enhanced communication should be supported
-	It should value the time physicians spend using technology for the monitoring of clinical data
-	Payments for care management services should not result in deduction in payments for face-to-face service
-	Payment “should recognize case mix differences in the patient population being treated within the practice”
-	It should allow physicians to share in the savings from reduced hospitalizations 
-	It should allow for additional compensation for achieving measurable and continuous quality improvements

A survey of 3,535 U.S. adults released in 2007 found that 27% of the respondents reported having "four indicators of a medical home."<ref name=Beal2007>{{cite web |author=Beal AC, Doty MM, Hernandez SE, Shea KK, Davis K |url=http://www.commonwealthfund.org/~/media/Files/Publications/Fund%20Report/2007/Jun/Closing%20the%20Divide%20%20How%20Medical%20Homes%20Promote%20Equity%20in%20Health%20Care%20%20Results%20From%20The%20Commonwealth%20F/1035_Beal_closing_divide_medical_homes%20pdf.pdf |title=Closing the divide: how medical homes promote equity in health care. Results from The Commonwealth Fund 2006 Health Care Quality Survey |location=New York |publisher=The Commonwealth Fund |date=2007 Jun |accessdate=2009-07-14}}</ref> Furthermore, having a medical home was associated with better access to care, more preventive screenings, higher quality of care, and fewer racial and ethnic disparities.<ref name=Beal2007/>

Important 2008–2010 developments concerning medical homes included:
* The [[Accreditation Association for Ambulatory Health Care]] (AAAHC) began accrediting medical homes in 2009 and is the only accrediting body to conduct on-site survey for organizations seeking Medical Home [[accreditation]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Accreditation Association for Ambulatory Health Care]] |url=http://www.aaahc.org/eweb/dynamicpage.aspx?webcode=mha |title=Medical Home Accreditation |accessdate=2010 March 30}}</ref>
* The [[National Committee for Quality Assurance]] released ''Physician Practice Connections–Patient-Centered Medical Home'' (PPC-PCMH), a set of voluntary standards for the recognition of physician practices as medical homes.<ref>{{cite web |author=National Committee for Quality Assurance |url=http://www.ncqa.org/tabid/631/Default.aspx |title=Physician Practice Connections–Patient-Centered Medical Home (PPC-PCMH) |accessdate=2009 Jul 14}}</ref>
* In answering a 2008 survey from the American Academy of Family Physicians, then-presidential candidate [[Barack Obama]] wrote "I support the concept of a patient-centered medical home"<ref name=Obama2008>{{cite web |url=http://my.barackobama.com/page/community/post/sultanr/gGxkpL |title=Obama responds to American Academy of Family Physicians. |publisher=BarackObama.com |date=2008-07-15 |accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref> and that as president he would "encourage and provide appropriate payment for providers who implement the medical home model".<ref name=Backer2009/><ref name=Arnst2009/><ref name=Obama2008/>
